'''Miminashi Yamaguchi Shrine''' (みみなしやまぐちじんじゃ) is a shrine on {{ill|lt=Mount Miminashi|Q11610730|qid=Q11610730|1=Mount Miminashi}} (one of the {{ill|lt=Yamato Sanzan|Q1470150|qid=Q1470150|1=Yamato Sanzan}}) in {{ill|lt=Kashihara|Q496319|qid=Q496319|1=Kashihara, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|qid=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. Though called a {{ill|lt=Yamaguchi Shrine|Q11467399|qid=Q11467399|1=Yamaguchi Shrine}}, it is not at the mountain foot but around the eight-tenths point up the mountain. It is one of the six Yamaguchi shrines of {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|qid=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}} (Asuka, Ishimura, {{ill|lt=Unebiyamaguchi Shrine|Q11578590|qid=Q11578590|lt=Unebi|1=Unebiyamaguchi Shrine}}, Osa, Hase, and '''Miminashi''') and was worshiped as the mountain deity of timber-cutting mountains for {{ill|lt=Imperial Household|Q909452|qid=Q909452|1=Imperial House of Japan}} buildings. Also in the precinct are {{ill|lt=Kotohira Shrine|Q11646488|qid=Q11646488|1=Kotohira shrines}}, {{ill|lt=Inari Shrine|Q514480|qid=Q514480|1=Inari shrine}}, and {{ill|lt=Hakuryū Daijin|Q123407570|qid=Q123407570|1=Hakuryū Daijin}}.

It is said to grant blessings for safe childbirth.

=== History ===
Its founding is unclear<ref>There is a theory that it was founded by an oracle in the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Seimu|Q316672|qid=Q316672|1=Emperor Seimu}}.</ref>, but old records state that in {{ill|lt=730|Q23563|qid=Q23563|1=730}} (Tenpyō 2) in the {{ill|lt=Shōsōin documents|Q11545362|qid=Q11545362|1=Shōsōin Documents}} {{ill|lt=tax register|Q11545592|qid=Q11545592|1=tax register}}, the shrine received rice from the {{ill|lt=emperor|Q208233|qid=Q208233|1=Emperor of Japan}}, and that in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} it was listed as a {{ill|lt=great shrine|Q11438310|qid=Q11438310|1=Taisha (shrine)}} and charged with {{ill|lt=Tsukinami-sai|Q11516161|qid=Q11516161|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}} and {{ill|lt=Niiname-sai|Q11501518|qid=Q11501518|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}} rites. Records also remain that in {{ill|lt=806|Q30021|qid=Q30021|1=806}} (Daidō 1) and in {{ill|lt=859|Q23897|qid=Q23897|1=859}} (Jōgan 1), imperial envoys conducted {{ill|lt=rain-prayer|Q477738|qid=Q477738|1=Rainmaking (ritual)}} rituals.

In {{ill|lt=1651|Q6956|qid=Q6956|1=1651}} (Keian 4), villagers of Yamanobō cut and damaged sacred trees, triggering disputes over mountain management and ownership centered on the shrine. In {{ill|lt=1702|Q6819|qid=Q6819|1=1702}} (Genroku 15), it was settled by identifying “Miminashiyama Tenjin” as the shikinaisha Miminashi Yamaguchi Shrine. After that, Yamanobō villagers transferred the divine spirit to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yamanobō Yamaguchi Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref>''Great Encyclopedia of Temples and Shrines (Yamato/Kii)'' ({{ill|lt=Heibonsha|Q11482108|qid=Q11482108|1=Heibonsha}})</ref>. During this period, buildings were burned and fell into disrepair, but in August {{ill|lt=1748|Q7600|qid=Q7600|1=1748}} (Kan'en 1), parishioners of {{ill|lt=Miminashi Village|Q17175746|qid=Q17175746|1=Miminashi}} rebuilt the current {{ill|lt=honden|Q2044994|qid=Q2044994|1=Honden}} and {{ill|lt=haiden|Q3125745|qid=Q3125745|1=Haiden (Shinto)}}, and the shrine came to be worshiped as the {{ill|lt=ujigami|Q767655|qid=Q767655|1=Ujigami}} of Ishiharada, Kihara, Kuzumoto, Shinga, Tokiwa, and Yamanobō districts.

